  "prompt": "Is it true ousting of Sucha Singh Chhotepur was done to higher the chances of Kejriwal for becoming CM Punjab?",
  "response": "The ousting of Sucha Singh Chhotepur as the AAP's (Aam Aadmi Party) Punjab convener in 2016 was a significant event that stirred considerable controversy within the party and among political observers. Chhotepur was sacked amid allegations of accepting bribes, specifically cash-for-tickets, which he vehemently denied.\n\nWhile some speculated that his removal was orchestrated to clear the path for Arvind Kejriwal, the then-national convenor of AAP, to potentially become the Chief Minister of Punjab, there is no concrete evidence to support this claim. The official reason given by the party for Chhotepur's removal was the bribery allegations.\n\nKejriwal did campaign extensively in Punjab and was considered a frontrunner for the CM post if AAP won the elections. However, AAP's poor performance in the 2017 Punjab Assembly elections led to the party not forming the government, and Kejriwal did not become the Chief Minister.\n\nIn summary, while the removal of Chhotepur might have been seen by some as a move to strengthen Kejriwal's position within the party, the primary stated reason was the bribery scandal. The actual impact on Kejriwal's chances of becoming CM remains speculative and was ultimately overshadowed by AAP's electoral defeat in 2017.",
